08:47.004 --> 08:50.312
DONNIE:
He can lay there
and think about what he did.

08:52.227 --> 08:55.796
MAN:
[groans]

08:55.883 --> 08:57.928
BRENTON:
You're starting
to scare me, Donnie.

08:58.015 --> 09:00.148
DONNIE: Anybody that fools
around with Bean
ought to be scared.

09:00.235 --> 09:02.324
BRENTON:
Yeah but you can't go off trying
to kill a man over it.

09:02.411 --> 09:03.804
DONNIE:
He ain't dead.

09:03.891 --> 09:05.066
BRENTON:
Damn near it.

09:05.153 --> 09:10.811
[footsteps]

09:28.742 --> 09:31.048
[♪♪♪]

09:31.135 --> 09:32.876
[radio static]

09:32.963 --> 09:35.096
MAN:
-- not one of us can deny
the carnival of wickedness

09:35.183 --> 09:37.054
has come to our humble town.

09:37.141 --> 09:39.404
But for this we cannot
place blame on the lawyered

09:39.491 --> 09:42.669
statesmen who
poisoned our waters,

09:42.756 --> 09:45.193
or the foreigner who hides
behind his mongering threats

09:45.280 --> 09:47.543
of violence, for while

09:47.630 --> 09:49.893
the physical bomb has yet to
becloud Minston County,

09:49.980 --> 09:53.462
there is one who works
tirelessly on our behalf,

09:53.549 --> 09:57.118
even as we're baptized in
the blood of perversion.

09:57.205 --> 09:59.729
But let us not forget the
progress we have made under

09:59.816 --> 10:02.776
the rule of Mr Bascum, whose
mechanisms of justice have

10:02.863 --> 10:06.127
freed us from our
past perversions.

10:06.214 --> 10:09.696
The foolish among you may
protest the severity of his

10:09.783 --> 10:13.003
methods, but a true countryman
never questions the need for

10:13.090 --> 10:18.530
order and enforcement.

10:18.618 --> 10:20.924
DONNIE:
It's supposed to be
a real current treatment.

10:21.011 --> 10:23.927
I know you hate the idea of
being injected with something,

10:24.014 --> 10:29.454
but I'll be back first
thing to check on you.

10:29.541 --> 10:31.718
I'll try and bring Bean, too.

10:31.805 --> 10:35.417
[♪♪♪]

10:35.504 --> 10:40.901
DONNIE:
But I think we
got reason to be hopeful.

10:40.988 --> 10:44.078
BARBARA:
There ain't nothing
hopeful about this place.

10:44.165 --> 10:45.340
[♪♪♪]

10:45.427 --> 10:53.478
[smacking]

10:55.480 --> 11:00.181
♪ [intense music]

11:00.268 --> 11:02.139
[silence]

11:06.143 --> 11:08.580
[door creeks open]

11:11.801 --> 11:14.761
BEAN:
I already boiled some.

11:14.848 --> 11:17.415
[clatter]

11:17.502 --> 11:18.852
DONNIE:
You get supper?

11:18.939 --> 11:20.636
BEAN:
I'm fine.

11:20.723 --> 11:22.856
DONNIE:
Sorry I didn't
bring anything home.

11:22.943 --> 11:24.466
[clatter]

11:24.553 --> 11:25.815
DONNIE:
Wanted to see Bab
before they started

11:25.902 --> 11:29.253
the new treatment.

11:29.340 --> 11:30.907
Going back first thing
if you want to come.

11:30.994 --> 11:36.696
BEAN:
No, thank you.

11:36.783 --> 11:38.045
DONNIE:
Alright, I can see
you're on about something.

11:38.132 --> 11:42.658
Just let it out.

11:42.745 --> 11:44.921
BEAN:
I heard you gave
it to Professor Nickens.

11:45.008 --> 11:47.619
Sent him to the
clinic and everything?

11:47.707 --> 11:48.751
DONNIE:
That man shouldn't
have been alone in my house

11:48.838 --> 11:50.144
with you.

11:50.231 --> 11:52.102
BEAN:
He's my
calculations teacher.

11:52.189 --> 11:54.017
He was helping me study.

11:54.104 --> 11:55.453
DONNIE:
He can help folks with
their educational work

11:55.540 --> 11:57.717
at the educational facility.

11:57.804 --> 12:02.765
Not in my house alone with
my 14-year-old sister.

12:05.246 --> 12:07.944
Bean, you're too young to
understand the intentions

12:08.031 --> 12:09.990
of men.

12:10.077 --> 12:11.992
I did what I did and
it was for the best.

12:12.079 --> 12:13.733
[clatter]

12:19.477 --> 12:20.522
DONNIE:
You take it.

12:20.609 --> 12:23.568
I'm heading to Mr Harold's.

12:23.655 --> 12:26.484
MAN:
Why do we question
behavior [indistinct]

12:26.571 --> 12:28.138
punishment.

12:28.225 --> 12:30.358
Without enforcement the
hard-working laborer is but

12:30.445 --> 12:32.882
putty in the hands of evil.

12:32.969 --> 12:35.885
So we must make examples of
the woman who sells her body

12:35.972 --> 12:40.760
and the man who has
turned to [indistinct]

12:40.847 --> 12:42.674
We must not think of--.

12:42.762 --> 12:45.025
WOMAN:
[breaths deeply]

12:45.112 --> 12:48.376
♪ [humming]

12:48.463 --> 12:50.508
My, that is low.

12:50.595 --> 12:52.554
[clears throat]

12:52.641 --> 12:57.037
♪ [melodic humming]

12:59.604 --> 13:03.565
WOMAN:
How'd the boy do today?

13:03.652 --> 13:08.048
MILT:
He lived up
to his reputation.

13:08.135 --> 13:11.660
Rhoda, I'm famished.

13:11.747 --> 13:15.620
What do you say we head into
the local meat shop and

13:15.707 --> 13:19.581
devour us some lamb tips?

13:19.668 --> 13:22.976
RHODA:
It's a bit
early for supper.

13:23.063 --> 13:30.331
MILT:
Rhoda, you are a cherry
red tulip that's always

13:30.418 --> 13:33.595
in full bloom.

13:33.682 --> 13:38.208
RHODA:
Save the flattery until we've
finished the task at hand.

13:38.295 --> 13:41.821
[rustling]

13:45.476 --> 13:49.698
MILT:
And to waste these
fine motel furnishings.

13:51.265 --> 13:59.273
[♪♪♪]

14:06.236 --> 14:14.244
[squeaking]

14:14.331 --> 14:16.116
[distant ruckus]

14:16.203 --> 14:20.511
MAN:
Give it to me!

14:20.598 --> 14:21.991
HAROLD:
This ain't
no damn orphanage.

14:22.078 --> 14:23.340
This is a place of business.

14:23.427 --> 14:24.994
MAN:
Give me the pillows!

14:25.081 --> 14:27.475
HAROLD:
We're not gonna--
get out of here, shoo!

14:27.562 --> 14:29.216
Shoo!

14:29.303 --> 14:30.347
MAN:
Gah!

14:30.434 --> 14:31.392
Damn it!

14:31.479 --> 14:33.307
[door slams]

14:34.699 --> 14:36.310
HAROLD:
Thanks, Donnie.

14:36.397 --> 14:40.227
But I don't need you
mucking around in my mud.

14:40.314 --> 14:42.446
DONNIE:
Every business in
town has a night patrol.

14:42.533 --> 14:46.537
I'm just doing my job.

14:46.624 --> 14:50.237
HAROLD:
It ain't a job if you
ain't getting compensated.

14:52.195 --> 14:54.676
