for a bit.

20:09.077 --> 20:10.731
[chickens clucking]

20:10.818 --> 20:12.254
BRENTON:
What have we got?

20:12.341 --> 20:14.256
DONNIE: It looks like
two females and a rooster.

20:14.343 --> 20:16.084
BRENTON:
Oh boy, you're
getting good at that.

20:16.171 --> 20:18.608
DONNIE:
It ain't hard.

20:18.695 --> 20:19.827
See the point on this one?

20:19.914 --> 20:21.132
BRENTON:
I see it.

20:21.220 --> 20:22.743
It's a rooster, right?

20:22.830 --> 20:24.832
DONNIE:
That's right.

20:24.919 --> 20:28.531
BRENTON:
If it's round
like this one, it's a lady?

20:28.618 --> 20:31.926
DONNIE:
You gotta take into
account the texture, too.

20:32.013 --> 20:33.536
The rooster surface
is much rougher.

20:33.623 --> 20:35.277
BRENTON:
Oh.

20:35.364 --> 20:38.672
That's why you're
the master egg sexer.

20:39.890 --> 20:47.550
♪ [intense music] ♪

20:47.637 --> 20:54.992
[footsteps]

20:55.079 --> 20:58.257
[alarm sounding]

21:04.045 --> 21:06.700
[door creaking]

21:25.806 --> 21:29.418
[door creaking]

21:32.943 --> 21:35.903
[squeaking]

21:46.130 --> 21:47.131
[clatter]

21:47.218 --> 21:48.829
[chains rattle]

21:48.916 --> 21:56.358
[rustling]

21:56.445 --> 22:01.972
[grunting]

22:02.059 --> 22:10.067
[rattling footsteps]

22:29.043 --> 22:30.653
HAROLD:
Mr. Bascum?

22:30.740 --> 22:32.089
BASCUM:
Harold.

22:34.788 --> 22:36.659
Your ledger, please.

22:50.847 --> 22:54.764
BASCUM:
Oh.

22:54.851 --> 22:57.245
Harold,
I'll be frank.

22:57.332 --> 23:00.335
The talk around town is that
you've been allowing some

23:00.422 --> 23:06.254
unsavory clientele into
your establishment.

23:06.341 --> 23:10.084
It's now clear that you
falsified your records to

23:10.171 --> 23:12.478
conceal your wrongdoing.

23:12.565 --> 23:16.351
Which disappoints
me even more.

23:16.438 --> 23:19.223
HAROLD:
Well, as you can
tell by our pillow stacks,

23:19.310 --> 23:23.010
we ain't exactly
selling out rooms.

23:23.097 --> 23:25.229
BASCUM:
Yes but you're well
aware of the moral standards

23:25.316 --> 23:28.494
we're all required to uphold.

23:28.581 --> 23:31.018
HAROLD:
I offer comfortable
accommodations.

23:31.105 --> 23:34.543
You buy a pillow,
you get a room.

23:34.630 --> 23:38.721
I'm not here to pry into
my patron's affairs.

23:38.808 --> 23:42.290
BASCUM:
But these patrons
are promoting a culture of

23:42.377 --> 23:47.338
addiction and degradation.

23:47.426 --> 23:50.603
The well-being of Minston
is more important than your

23:50.690 --> 23:54.128
profit/loss margin.

23:54.215 --> 23:57.044
HAROLD:
So what am
I supposed to do?

23:57.131 --> 23:59.481
Turn away paying countrymen?

23:59.568 --> 24:02.441
Because of your
unwritten rules?

24:09.099 --> 24:13.713
BASCUM:
I expected more
gratitude from you, Harold.

24:13.800 --> 24:18.065
I've labored greatly to ensure
the negro is fairly judged in

24:18.152 --> 24:24.201
this community, and yet you
still chose to dishonor us.

24:24.288 --> 24:28.467
In front of my son, no less.

24:28.554 --> 24:32.166
I'm afraid we'll
have to address this.

24:32.993 --> 24:35.474
Put him up here.

24:35.561 --> 24:37.127
[grunting]

24:37.214 --> 24:41.262
[shuffling]

24:41.349 --> 24:43.917
BASCUM:
Your ankle.

24:44.004 --> 24:48.704
[rustling]

24:53.013 --> 24:56.016
HAROLD:
[whimpers]

24:56.103 --> 25:02.631
[rustling]

25:12.075 --> 25:13.729
BASCUM:
Your blade.

25:22.825 --> 25:27.090
This is not
something I relish.

25:27.177 --> 25:29.136
But we must stand
by our principles.

25:29.223 --> 25:35.142
[screaming]

25:35.229 --> 25:37.274
BASCUM:
Gentle with him.

25:37.361 --> 25:45.413
[muffled screaming]

26:08.175 --> 26:12.222
[rattling footsteps]

26:12.309 --> 26:15.617
BASCUM:
I understand you'll likely view
my methods as harsh.

26:15.704 --> 26:20.013
But this town totters
on the edge of ruin.

26:20.100 --> 26:25.148
Can you imagine it without
ethical enforcement?

26:25.235 --> 26:29.196
♪ [tense music]

26:29.283 --> 26:34.331
[braces rattle]

26:39.989 --> 26:41.077
[thud]

26:41.164 --> 26:43.471
[♪♪♪]

26:43.558 --> 26:47.083
BASCUM:
Just the toes.

26:47.170 --> 26:51.218
[muffled screaming]

26:51.305 --> 26:59.313
[♪♪♪]

27:05.841 --> 27:07.538
[thud]

27:07.626 --> 27:09.366
SHERI:
It's flat out wicked.

27:09.453 --> 27:12.587
But we need to stay hopeful.

27:12.674 --> 27:21.335
A man can live years
without his toes.

27:21.422 --> 27:26.906
I'm gonna go out back
and needle some chuckeye.

27:26.993 --> 27:31.911
I need something pure to
wash my mind of all this.

27:31.998 --> 27:36.655
[pats]

27:40.049 --> 27:43.400
[dishes clatter]

27:45.925 --> 27:48.754
[door squeaks]

27:51.060 --> 27:53.933
MILT:
From what I hear it
could have been his leg.

27:56.936 --> 28:02.028
I have travelled from Grand
Forks to the [indistinct]

28:02.115 --> 28:05.379
bottom and back.

28:05.466 --> 28:10.645
And I've never seen a
man as twisted as Bascum.

28:10.732 --> 28:12.995
When your method of justice
is cutting of limbs,

28:13.082 --> 28:17.043
instilling fear into the
innocent people of this town,

28:17.130 --> 28:19.785
yeah.

28:19.872 --> 28:25.704
I think you deserve
to be boiled alive.

28:25.791 --> 28:27.706
DONNIE:
Best of luck with that.

28:27.793 --> 28:31.927
MILT:
I don't need luck,
I need you, Donnie.

28:32.014 --> 28:34.582
See, I believe you and I can
give that gutless vulture

28:34.669 --> 28:38.238
the justice he deserves.

28:38.325 --> 28:42.546
I know I probably sound like
a bonafide kook right now.

28:42.633 --> 28:50.685
And I know this whole town
is living under his shadow.

28:50.772 --> 28:56.778
But I also know that
Minston deserves better.

28:56.865 --> 29:01.130
So why not do
something about it?

29:01.217 --> 29:03.567
DONNIE:
Your mind's all mangled.

29:03.654 --> 29:06.179
He can't be touched.

29:06.266 --> 29:07.702
MILT:
[scoffs]

29:07.789 --> 29:09.704
You're seeing things
through a magnifying glass.

29:09.791 --> 29:11.575
I'm handing you a telescope.

29:11.662 --> 29:13.273
If you chose to
look through it,

29:13.360 --> 29:17.756
I'll show you exactly how we
can carry out his sentence.

29:17.843 --> 29:21.760
DONNIE:
Why the hell would
I involve myself with you?

29:21.847 --> 29:24.806
MILT:
Because I know
about your mother.

29:24.893 --> 29:26.852
[rustling]

29:26.939 --> 29:29.115
MILT:
I don't ask for a man's
help without offering him

29:29.202 --> 29:30.812
something in return.

29:30.899 --> 29:32.509
I have read everything
there is to know about Bab's

29:32.596 --> 29:35.512
condition, I know the
prognosis seems bleak.

29:35.599 --> 29:39.342
I have reason to believe
there is still hope for her.

29:39.429 --> 29:42.345
♪ [tense music]

29:42.432 --> 29:49.091
[paper rumpling]

29:51.528 --> 29:55.532
MILT:
It's a modern marvel.

29:55.619 --> 29:59.710
A holistic approach
to healing the mind.

29:59.798 --> 30:06.282
And if you accept my proposal,
this could be Babs in reality.

30:06.369 --> 30:08.545
What do you say, Donnie?

30:08.632 --> 30:13.376
Will you help me take down
John Merryweather Bascum?

30:13.463 --> 30:15.814
[♪♪♪]

30:20.296 --> 30:25.693
[electricity buzzing]

30:25.780 --> 30:32.743
[steady breathing]

30:32.831 --> 30:38.880
DONNIE:
Gonna get you
the hell out of here.

30:38.967 --> 30:43.319
There's this behavioral
center up in Macoupin.

30:43.406 --> 30:48.934
[paper rustling]

30:49.021 --> 30:50.283
DONNIE:
I just found a way to
get us the money we

30:50.370 --> 30:56.115
need to get you there.

30:56.202 --> 31:00.815
BEAN:
Who the hell would
want someone's toes?

31:00.902 --> 31:03.949
DONNIE:
You don't need to
concern yourself over it.

31:04.036 --> 31:06.125
Just didn't want you hearing
it from the chatterheds.

31:06.212 --> 31:07.082
BEAN:
I thought that was why
you were there

31:07.169 --> 31:09.911
in the first place?

31:09.998 --> 31:13.610
DONNIE:
There's nothing
that could have been done.

31:13.697 --> 31:15.874
BEAN:
They're all a
bunch of philistines.

31:15.961 --> 31:18.267
And you wonder why this
place is the way it is.

31:18.354 --> 31:20.530
DONNIE:
Hey, you
got no idea--.

31:20.617 --> 31:22.619
Mr Harold's pillow stack.

31:22.706 --> 31:24.752
And you just sit there
and let it happen,

31:24.839 --> 31:27.059
thinking you're
somehow blameless.

31:27.146 --> 31:28.103
[knocking]

31:28.190 --> 31:31.498
[footsteps retreating]

31:31.585 --> 31:33.195
BEAN:
He's not coming.

31:33.282 --> 31:34.588
[door slams]

31:34.675 --> 31:43.031
♪ [morose music]

31:43.118 --> 31:45.381
MILT:
Wrap your mind
around a new way of battle.

31:45.468 --> 31:47.644
'Cause your days of waltzing
up to a man and overpowering

31:47.731 --> 31:51.648
him with your
knuckles are over.

31:51.735 --> 31:54.129
To take down a man
of Bascum's stature,

31:54.216 --> 31:56.131
we'll need to be prepared.

31:56.218 --> 31:57.959
Covert.

31:58.046 --> 31:59.830
Deliberate.

31:59.918 --> 32:02.790
He's got a slew of brogues
watching his every move,

32:02.877 --> 32:05.097
but before we even think about
busting down his door and

32:05.184 --> 32:09.014
taking his currency, there are
facets of your mind and body

32:09.101 --> 32:11.538
that need sharpening, and
that's why we're here.

32:11.625 --> 32:18.240
You may question my methods,
but if you trust the process,

32:18.327 --> 32:20.764
believe me.

32:20.851 --> 32:25.465
You'll taste the fruit.

32:25.552 --> 32:26.640
Weakness.

32:26.727 --> 32:28.381
Everyone's got one.

32:28.468 --> 32:31.210
But the men who can recognize
it in themselves learn to

32:31.297 --> 32:33.299
overcome it.

32:33.386 --> 32:35.649
What's your weakness?

32:35.736 --> 32:37.042
DONNIE:
Don't have one.

32:37.129 --> 32:38.130
MILT:
[scoffs]

32:38.217 --> 32:40.306
Dig deeper.

32:40.393 --> 32:41.960
What's your weakness?

32:42.047 --> 32:46.051
What about that mile
wide temper of yours?

32:46.138 --> 32:50.707
We're not gonna have room for
one of Donnie's hissy fits

32:50.794 --> 32:56.235
when were in the thick
of Bascum's quarters.

32:58.933 --> 33:01.849
These darts won't kill you.

33:01.936 --> 33:03.894
Barely make you bleed.

33:03.982 --> 33:07.246
So there's no reason to
exclaim when they hit you.

33:07.333 --> 33:10.945
[squelch]

33:16.342 --> 33:22.043
MILT:
Did reacting
make you feel better?

33:22.130 --> 33:24.306
[squelch]

33:24.393 --> 33:25.960
MILT:
No.

33:26.047 --> 33:30.356
Reacting didn't do a damn
thing to ease your pain.

33:30.443 --> 33:36.144
Now when you can sit silent
for three in a row, I'll stop.

33:36.231 --> 33:37.363
Too much reaction.

33:37.450 --> 33:39.408
DONNIE:
I barely flinched.

33:39.495 --> 33:44.022
[squelch]

33:44.109 --> 33:49.027
MILT:
Control your emotions,
and it'll all be over.

33:49.114 --> 33:50.680
[squelch]

33:50.767 --> 33:51.812
[♪♪♪]

33:51.899 --> 33:55.294
DONNIE:
[grunts]

33:55.381 --> 33:56.991
MILT:
Switching to
your head, that's good,

33:57.078 --> 33:58.775
because I can give you
a little demonstration.

33:58.862 --> 34:00.647
Now when you put a hole
into one of his men,

34:00.734 --> 34:02.779
you take the dart
and you stab him.

34:02.866 --> 34:04.564
But don't just stab once.

34:04.651 --> 34:07.262
You keep stabbing until you
pierce that artery and he lies

34:07.349 --> 34:08.916
dead in your arms.

34:09.003 --> 34:11.875
DONNIE:
Argh!

34:15.009 --> 34:16.184
MILT:
Don't worry.

34:16.271 --> 34:17.925
You'll be fine.

34:18.012 --> 34:19.927
But if I'd line those with the
venom of a strawberry poison

34:20.014 --> 34:23.061
frog, you wouldn't be.

34:23.148 --> 34:25.193
DONNIE:
What the fuck
is wrong with you?

34:25.280 --> 34:27.413
MILT:
[chuckles]
Wrong with me?

34:27.500 --> 34:30.590
We're trying to take down
a militia and you can't absorb

34:30.677 --> 34:35.985
a few pinpricks without
turning into a circus chimp.

34:36.074 --> 34:38.815
If you give a damn
about your mother,

34:38.902 --> 34:41.818
you will give me
what I ask for.

34:45.257 --> 34:48.042
[fly buzzing]

34:50.739 --> 34:52.786
MILT:
Your turn.

34:53.830 --> 34:59.009
[footsteps approaching]

35:03.013 --> 35:07.366
[rattling approaching]

35:12.893 --> 35:15.113
[door opens]

35:18.681 --> 35:19.813
[engine idling]

35:19.900 --> 35:28.300
[♪♪♪]

35:28.387 --> 35:32.652
[footsteps]

35:32.739 --> 35:36.830
[distant whimpering]

35:36.917 --> 35:39.354
[footsteps]

35:39.441 --> 35:47.449
♪ [operatic music]

35:51.105 --> 35:52.019
BASCUM:
Welcome.

35:52.106 --> 36:00.158
♪ [operatic music]

36:03.639 --> 36:11.256
[distant moaning]

36:12.344 --> 36:13.649
MAN:
[sighs]

36:13.736 --> 36:21.744
♪ [operatic music]

36:27.446 --> 36:31.189
DONNIE:
These look real
promising, Mr Harold.

36:31.276 --> 36:36.585
Stronger than most men's toes.

36:36.672 --> 36:41.895
HAROLD:
I have no interest
in becoming a machine.

36:45.855 --> 36:48.423
DONNIE:
Hey Mr Harold, if
there was anything I could

36:48.510 --> 36:49.511
have done different--.

36:56.518 --> 36:59.913
MAN:
And the sorrowful state
[indistinct] illustrated in

37:00.000 --> 37:04.091
the advertisements on the
back of your soup cans.

37:04.178 --> 37:07.921
But why lust for what we fail
to earn when the hands of our

37:08.008 --> 37:10.967
distance enemies threaten
what little we do possess?

37:11.054 --> 37:13.100
[breaks screech]

37:13.187 --> 37:15.494
MAN:
Why yearn for more when
our current residence are but

37:15.581 --> 37:20.020
a bumbling button push
from complete eradication.

37:20.107 --> 37:23.632
I ask you this day to remember
a time, a childhood time,

37:23.719 --> 37:28.246
when most of us enjoyed a
happy home not-- [indistinct]

37:28.333 --> 37:36.341
[radio fades]

37:40.693 --> 37:42.651
MILT:
Hello?

37:42.738 --> 37:47.090
[squelching]

37:47.177 --> 37:49.049
MILT:
Perfect timing.

37:49.136 --> 37:51.660
I just prepared
some mixed meats.

37:51.747 --> 37:54.533
RHODA:
I've no appetite.

37:57.753 --> 38:05.195
MILT:
Did you...
dine...with him?

38:05.283 --> 38:08.851
RHODA:
Why do you pursue
needless exposition?

38:08.938 --> 38:13.421
MILT:
My imagination
torments me.

38:13.508 --> 38:18.165
RHODA:
Some of us don't have the luxury
of simply imagining.

38:18.252 --> 38:22.996
I'll confirm the location
of his currency tomorrow.

38:23.083 --> 38:26.260
The layout is simpler
than I thought.

38:26.347 --> 38:32.527
MILT:
Rhoda, I can't imagine
the turmoil your mind and body

38:32.614 --> 38:34.355
are enduring right now.

38:34.442 --> 38:37.793
RHODA:
I can perform as
long as is necessary.

38:37.880 --> 38:40.405
[clink]

38:43.582 --> 38:51.241
[chickens clucking]

38:51.329 --> 38:53.243
DONNIE:
Alright, I gotta split.

38:53.331 --> 38:54.941
BRENTON:
Hey, you know, maybe
I could come along with you.

38:55.028 --> 38:56.159
I gotta get some
wood supplies from--.

38:56.246 --> 38:57.509
DONNIE:
No, I'm fine.

38:57.596 --> 38:58.553
BRENTON: Oh, what
direction you headed?

38:58.640 --> 38:59.989
Maybe I could just come--.

39:00.076 --> 39:01.426
DONNIE: You don't need
to concern yourself.

39:01.513 --> 39:03.166
Just pay attention
to those eggs, Brenton.

39:03.253 --> 39:04.603
BRENTON: If you can't tell
your friend and colleague what

39:04.690 --> 39:06.169
you've been up to,
you ever consider

39:06.256 --> 39:07.562
maybe you shouldn't be doing it?

39:07.649 --> 39:10.173
[chickens cluck]

39:16.832 --> 39:19.487
[chirping]

39:19.574 --> 39:21.533
MILT:
I got something
to show you.

39:22.621 --> 39:25.537
[chirping]

39:28.278 --> 39:32.631
MILT:
All females, except one.

39:32.718 --> 39:34.546
You get yourself a
few males together,

39:34.633 --> 39:36.199
you have yourself a war.

39:36.286 --> 39:38.637
Now those [indistinct]
bastards down near the Equator

39:38.724 --> 39:40.943
used to roast these poor
creatures alive

39:41.030 --> 39:42.597
to extract the venom.

39:42.684 --> 39:45.774
But all you really gotta
do is prick your tip

39:45.861 --> 39:47.820
right behind--...

39:54.348 --> 39:56.437
DONNIE:
Who's that?

39:56.524 --> 39:59.092
[chirping]

39:59.179 --> 40:02.400
MILT:
Woman leading
us to Bascum.

40:06.491 --> 40:08.406
[chirping]

40:12.105 --> 40:17.806
♪ [operatic music]

40:17.893 --> 40:19.242
BASCUM:
You look ravishing.

40:19.329 --> 40:20.635
RHODA:
Thank you, John.

40:20.722 --> 40:28.730
♪ [operatic music]

40:30.689 --> 40:32.647
[rattling]

40:32.734 --> 40:38.131
[engine starts]

40:42.744 --> 40:50.752
♪ [operatic music]

41:08.944 --> 41:12.687
BASCUM:
Warren, it's
not polite to stare.

41:12.774 --> 41:15.516
Face forward, please.

41:20.129 --> 41:28.137
♪ [operatic music intensifies]

41:34.753 --> 41:38.191
[silence]

41:44.589 --> 41:46.939
[door opens]

41:51.857 --> 41:55.382
[rustling]

42:07.437 --> 42:09.352
MILT:
Hand me that beaker.

42:16.751 --> 42:20.233
Go on, take a swig.

42:20.320 --> 42:22.844
We're gonna be here a while.

42:24.846 --> 42:27.022
[♪♪♪]

42:27.109 --> 42:35.727
BASCUM:
[groaning]

42:35.814 --> 42:37.119
Can you help me, dear?

42:37.206 --> 42:42.168
[♪♪♪]

42:42.255 --> 42:49.305
BASCUM:
[groans]

42:53.309 --> 42:56.051
Such a joy to have
your company again.

42:56.138 --> 43:01.448
RHODA:
Likewise.

43:04.494 --> 43:08.890
BASCUM:
I never imagined
we'd become [indistinct]

43:08.977 --> 43:10.849
RHODA:
Does it bother you?

43:10.936 --> 43:12.111
BASCUM:
Heavens no.

43:12.198 --> 43:13.721
[fabric tears]

43:13.808 --> 43:16.419
RHODA:
Oh my.

43:16.506 --> 43:18.247
BASCUM:
Is everything alright?

43:18.334 --> 43:22.251
RHODA:
I seem to have torn my
dress on your brace buckle.

43:22.338 --> 43:25.037
BASCUM:
Oh.

43:25.124 --> 43:26.995
You must be compensated.

43:29.258 --> 43:32.871
[groans]

43:32.958 --> 43:36.831
[braces rattle]

43:36.918 --> 43:38.877
BASCUM:
Ah.

43:58.592 --> 44:02.727
Take that to the Tender
Exchange after you depart.

44:03.684 --> 44:05.512
I insist.

44:05.599 --> 44:09.211
RHODA:
That's very
generous of you.

44:09.298 --> 44:10.865
BASCUM:
It's my pleasure.

44:13.128 --> 44:15.261
MILT:
We have pretty strong
confirmation what to expect

44:15.348 --> 44:17.567
down this corridor.

44:17.655 --> 44:20.309
Might see some resistance
here, possibly here.

44:20.396 --> 44:23.051
But then it's a straight
shot to the room.

44:23.138 --> 44:26.489
You take this, I'll split
off down the other passage.

44:26.576 --> 44:29.884
If all goes well, we'll
arrive seconds apart.

44:29.971 --> 44:32.800
The lumpy tyrant will be
positioned on the bed,

44:32.887 --> 44:36.935
and here is where we suspect
he keeps his currency,

44:37.022 --> 44:41.156
and damn it Donnie, every
ounce of legal tender in there

44:41.243 --> 44:43.202
is going to be yours.

44:43.289 --> 44:45.117
For Bab.

44:48.511 --> 44:51.427
DONNIE:
What's in it for you?

44:51.514 --> 44:53.255
MILT:
[laughing]

44:53.342 --> 44:55.083
Hell.

44:55.170 --> 44:58.130
All of it.

44:58.217 --> 45:01.611
Knocking down his door.

45:01.699 --> 45:06.965
Firing the dart straight
into his potato belly.

45:07.052 --> 45:11.970
Watching his crooked body
seize up like a manikin,

45:12.057 --> 45:15.800
alive only in his mind, so
all he can do is look at me

45:15.887 --> 45:19.151
knowing exactly why
he's laying there,

45:19.238 --> 45:22.763
choking on his own saliva.

45:22.850 --> 45:25.766
[♪♪♪]

45:25.853 --> 45:28.726
MILT:
There's gonna be
plenty in it for me.

45:32.642 --> 45:34.862
BASCUM:
[groans]

45:38.213 --> 45:40.955
Do you remember this?

45:41.042 --> 45:44.002
RHODA:
It was Opal's.

45:44.089 --> 45:46.091
BASCUM:
Yes.

45:46.178 --> 45:48.833
I want you to have it.

45:48.920 --> 45:51.183
RHODA:
You know
I can't play it.

45:51.270 --> 45:54.577
BASCUM:
You don't
need to play it.

45:54.664 --> 45:57.058
But I'd like to
see you hold it.

46:05.501 --> 46:08.983
I know I wasn't always
wholesome with you

46:09.070 --> 46:13.814
before your maturation.

46:13.901 --> 46:16.991
But I want you to know,
my affection for you

46:17.078 --> 46:23.084
has always been sincere.

46:23.171 --> 46:28.786
I treasured this opportunity
we've been granted.

46:29.917 --> 46:32.224
[knocking]

46:32.311 --> 46:34.835
BASCUM:
Why on earth!?

46:34.922 --> 46:37.533
[rattling]

46:37.620 --> 46:39.361
MAN:
Warren escaped.

46:39.448 --> 46:47.456
[♪♪♪]

46:49.284 --> 46:57.858
[footsteps approaching]

46:57.945 --> 47:02.950
DONNIE:
Hey, hey hey,
someone's coming.

47:04.560 --> 47:06.954
MILT:
Grab the darts.

47:11.741 --> 47:13.004
DONNIE:
He's coming right at us.

47:13.091 --> 47:16.311
MILT:
There's no
way he can see us.

47:16.398 --> 47:18.009
[distant shouting]

47:18.096 --> 47:22.622
[footsteps quicken]

47:22.709 --> 47:27.540
MILT:
You keep these with you.

47:27.627 --> 47:30.282
Be mindful of the tip.

47:30.369 --> 47:34.155
[♪♪♪]

48:01.530 --> 48:09.538
♪ [tense music]

49:15.517 --> 49:20.479
BASCUM:
[moaning]

49:20.566 --> 49:28.574
♪ [tense music]

49:41.282 --> 49:46.026
[silence]

49:46.113 --> 49:50.900
MILT:
Leather-faced
fella's back.

49:50.988 --> 49:53.642
Two full cycles
through the rotation?

49:53.729 --> 49:57.081
DONNIE:
Yep.

49:57.168 --> 50:01.128
MILT:
They're regimented,
that's for sure.

50:01.215 --> 50:03.261
Bodes well for us.

50:03.348 --> 50:06.612
This preparation is vital.

50:06.699 --> 50:08.179
Paramount.

50:08.266 --> 50:11.356
But it's not everything.

50:11.443 --> 50:14.402
You always got to be on
guard for the unknown.

50:14.489 --> 50:18.711
When I was younger
than your sister,

50:18.798 --> 50:24.064
I spent a sultry summer
on a wetland gulf.

50:24.151 --> 50:28.242
Every day I'd head out onto
the banks to track toads.

50:28.329 --> 50:30.331
That time of year, they'd
trounce themselves in the mud

50:30.418 --> 50:32.072
to beat the heat.

50:32.159 --> 50:35.249
Well one day, I'm making my
way to the centre of the gully

50:35.336 --> 50:41.821
when I see an oversized Creole
man dipping his own honey.

50:41.908 --> 50:43.475
Everything in me knew
that if I was detected,

50:43.562 --> 50:46.478
he'd mince me alive.

50:46.565 --> 50:48.219
The men of that culture
were territorial with their

50:48.306 --> 50:50.177
breeding grounds.

50:50.264 --> 50:51.744
So I had two choices.

50:51.831 --> 50:52.919
I could either
sink into the mud,

50:53.006 --> 50:55.226
unsure if I'd
ever make it out,

50:55.313 --> 50:58.751
or I could risk letting that
inflamed porpoise of a man

50:58.838 --> 51:00.709
have his way with me.

51:00.796 --> 51:05.105
Needless to say-- Argh!

51:05.192 --> 51:07.499
[rustling]

51:13.722 --> 51:19.511
MAN:
[whimpering]

51:22.122 --> 51:23.906
DONNIE:
Get the fuck out of here.

51:26.561 --> 51:27.997
MAN:
[growls]

51:33.177 --> 51:34.134
DONNIE:
[gasping]

51:34.221 --> 51:35.222
You okay?

51:37.746 --> 51:39.835
You answer me.

51:39.922 --> 51:41.707
DONNIE:
He ain't normal.

51:41.794 --> 51:43.839
MILT:
He's one of them.

51:43.926 --> 51:46.842
And they're what stand
in between us and Bascum.

51:46.929 --> 51:48.409
So I suggested you bury
whatever the hell that was

51:48.496 --> 51:50.324
deep inside or else you're
going to fuck this up

51:50.411 --> 51:51.934
for all of us.

51:52.021 --> 51:54.502
Including your mother.

51:54.589 --> 51:57.679
Now let's get the
hell out of here.

51:57.766 --> 52:05.774
♪ [somber music]

52:23.879 --> 52:28.406
[footsteps]

52:28.493 --> 52:29.755
MAN:
Pst.

52:29.842 --> 52:32.627
Why not be a man who
dreams for himself?

52:32.714 --> 52:34.325
[laughing]

52:34.412 --> 52:36.240
It's you.

52:36.327 --> 52:39.460
Come closer.

52:39.547 --> 52:47.555
[♪♪♪]

52:52.125 --> 52:53.605
MAN:
Let's get
you calmed down.

52:53.692 --> 52:58.305
[distant shouting]

53:03.267 --> 53:05.182
[whistling]

53:07.358 --> 53:13.494
♪ [tense music]

53:25.027 --> 53:27.378
MAN:
Come out,
come out, come out.

53:31.556 --> 53:35.864
[♪♪♪]

53:35.951 --> 53:38.911
MAN:
Argh!

53:40.391 --> 53:48.355
♪ [tense music]

53:51.010 --> 53:52.664
MAN:
Come on, Rico.

53:52.751 --> 53:54.883
Come on, now.

53:54.970 --> 54:03.022
[♪♪♪]

54:14.860 --> 54:18.516
[footsteps]

54:19.647 --> 54:20.692
DONNIE:
[grunts]

54:20.779 --> 54:24.348
[gasping]

54:25.566 --> 54:27.568
HAROLD:
Damn it, Donnie.

54:27.655 --> 54:28.961
DONNIE:
What should I do?

54:29.048 --> 54:30.267
HAROLD:
Get him to the bunker.

54:30.354 --> 54:31.877
Go, go.

54:31.964 --> 54:34.140
DONNIE:
[grunts]

54:40.364 --> 54:42.366
[loud thud]

54:42.453 --> 54:49.808
[gasping]

54:49.895 --> 54:51.113
[door squeaks]

54:55.944 --> 55:02.951
[electricity buzzing]

55:03.038 --> 55:05.171
HAROLD:
Lord, I wish
you hadn't done that.

55:09.088 --> 55:13.048
If your mother had any
idea what was going on...

55:18.053 --> 55:20.317
I don't want you wasting
another night here.

55:24.930 --> 55:28.455
[footsteps]

55:39.423 --> 55:40.989
[door squeaks]

55:41.076 --> 55:42.730
DONNIE:
Bean.

55:45.472 --> 55:46.734
Bean, you here?

55:56.004 --> 55:58.572
[alarm sounds]

55:58.659 --> 55:59.747
[smash]

55:59.834 --> 56:04.448
[door slams]

56:04.535 --> 56:07.712
RHODA:
Shouldn't we mind the drill?

56:07.799 --> 56:09.627
BASCUM:
No need.

56:09.714 --> 56:12.673
It's merely a reminder
of what's possible.

56:14.588 --> 56:18.766
If they have nothing to
fear, they'll only wallow in

56:18.853 --> 56:22.161
pleasure and perversion.

56:26.295 --> 56:27.732
Ah.

56:27.819 --> 56:29.342
RHODA:
What is it?

56:30.735 --> 56:32.345
BASCUM:
Warren.

56:33.999 --> 56:37.176
He's never taken
kindly to the drills.

56:39.352 --> 56:41.659
I wish he were safely
in his quarters.

56:41.746 --> 56:43.051
Hmm.

56:43.138 --> 56:44.923
RHODA: Oh, surely
he'll return home soon.

56:45.010 --> 56:47.969
Perhaps for his evening stew.

56:48.056 --> 56:50.450
BASCUM:
He has
no sense of time.

56:50.537 --> 56:53.061
RHODA:
I'm sure in his own way
he has a sense of longing

56:53.148 --> 56:55.499
for his father.

56:58.893 --> 57:02.941
BASCUM:
Would you do
something special for me?

57:03.028 --> 57:04.856
To ease my pain?

57:06.423 --> 57:09.817
RHODA:
What would you like?

57:09.904 --> 57:14.866
BASCUM:
Would you disrobe
to the cadence of the siren?

57:14.953 --> 57:22.961
[distant siren]

57:36.540 --> 57:38.803
BASCUM:
Yes.

57:38.890 --> 57:42.633
[distant siren]

57:42.720 --> 57:50.728
[siren blaring]

58:23.151 --> 58:27.634
[siren stops]

58:27.721 --> 58:28.722
BRENTON:
2-3.

58:28.809 --> 58:31.116
Donnie, jeez.

58:31.203 --> 58:32.813
I hope you didn't
dodge the drill.

58:32.900 --> 58:34.206
DONNIE:
Was someone going
to tell me you're here?

58:34.293 --> 58:35.207
BEAN:
I've been
staying here for days,

58:35.294 --> 58:37.078
you just now noticed?

58:37.165 --> 58:38.863
DONNIE: I brought
you a platter.

58:38.950 --> 58:41.996
BEAN: Wouldn't you believe it?
They keep food in this house.

58:42.083 --> 58:44.259
You should see
if Bab wants it.

58:44.346 --> 58:45.478
DONNIE:
Hey, where
are you going?

58:45.565 --> 58:47.654
BRENTON:
Hey, I'm sorry Don.

58:47.741 --> 58:50.352
But uh, mother and
I have discussed it,

58:50.439 --> 58:51.963
and we think it'd be best if
Bean stayed with us

58:52.050 --> 58:54.531
for the time being.

58:54.618 --> 58:56.489
DONNIE:
That what you want?

58:56.576 --> 58:57.751
BEAN:
Sure as hell don't want
to be involved with whatever

58:57.838 --> 59:00.275
you're doing.

59:00.362 --> 59:01.407
DONNIE:
You'd better not
be filling her head with--.

59:01.494 --> 59:02.974
BRENTON:
Woah woah woah, look.

59:03.061 --> 59:04.410
I know I shouldn't have
been snooping, okay?

59:04.497 --> 59:06.630
But first I see you
assaulting a dummy,

59:06.717 --> 59:09.023
and then I see you doing who
knows what with some stranger

59:09.110 --> 59:10.851
and Mr Bascum?

59:10.938 --> 59:14.028
I'm not judging you, Donnie,
but I don't see how any

59:14.115 --> 59:15.552
of this could be right for Bean.

59:15.639 --> 59:18.206
DONNIE:
You got know
fucking idea, Brenton.

59:18.293 --> 59:20.121
[thud]

59:20.208 --> 59:22.036
DONNIE:
Brenton?

59:22.123 --> 59:24.212
Brenton.

59:24.299 --> 59:25.605
BEAN:
What'd you do to him?

59:25.692 --> 59:27.564
DONNIE:
Nothing.

59:27.651 --> 59:29.000
BEAN:
Come on, Brenton,
snap out of it.

59:29.087 --> 59:30.044
WOMAN:
[wailing]

59:30.131 --> 59:33.047
No, oh no.

59:33.134 --> 59:37.008
Oh, baby.

59:39.140 --> 59:41.882
BEAN:
You can leave now.

59:41.969 --> 59:43.101
DONNIE:
Let me help
you get him inside.

59:43.188 --> 59:44.493
BEAN:
We don't need you here.

59:44.581 --> 59:46.365
Just stay the hell away.

59:51.675 --> 59:55.896
[footsteps]

59:55.983 --> 59:56.984
BRENTON:
Argh, okay.

59:57.071 --> 59:59.465
♪ [operatic music]

59:59.552 --> 1:00:02.860
BASCUM:
She was a wider woman,
but very limber in her

1:00:02.947 --> 1:00:06.951
movements, as the
small man [indistinct],

1:00:07.038 --> 1:00:16.438
a voice would crescendo
with haunting precision.

1:00:16.525 --> 1:00:19.920
I only wish I could have
shared the majesty of that

1:00:20.007 --> 1:00:22.488
moment with you.

1:00:22.575 --> 1:00:24.969
MAN:
[distant] Mr Bascum!

1:00:25.056 --> 1:00:26.884
Mr Bascum!

1:00:26.971 --> 1:00:31.628
♪ [operatic music]

1:00:31.715 --> 1:00:33.630
BASCUM:
Tell me you found him.

1:00:33.717 --> 1:00:34.979
MAN:
I'm sorry to
say we haven't,

1:00:35.066 --> 1:00:36.502
but now we've got
more pressing matters.

1:00:36.589 --> 1:00:38.939
Carol Lanko's gone missing.

1:00:39.026 --> 1:00:41.681
Found this on the strip.

1:00:41.768 --> 1:00:44.031
I'm putting you
on a state of high alert.

1:00:44.118 --> 1:00:45.511
BASCUM:
I assume
it's necessary?

1:00:45.598 --> 1:00:47.818
MAN:
Until we know more,
I'd advise it.

1:00:47.905 --> 1:00:49.341
BASCUM:
Alright.

1:00:49.428 --> 1:00:52.170
As long as Warren
is still priority.

1:00:52.257 --> 1:00:55.608
RHODA:
Would you
take me with you?

1:00:55.695 --> 1:00:57.001
MAN:
I don't think that
would be prudent right now.

1:00:57.088 --> 1:00:59.612
RHODA:
Please.

1:00:59.699 --> 1:01:01.919
I've been trapped in this
dress for an unbecoming

1:01:02.006 --> 1:01:03.660
amount of time.

1:01:03.747 --> 1:01:05.009
BASCUM:
One would
never know it.

1:01:05.096 --> 1:01:06.967
You look as fresh as--.

1:01:07.054 --> 1:01:11.450
RHODA:
To be forthright, I have
a special performance planned.

1:01:11.537 --> 1:01:13.974
To do it without proper
rehearsal would

1:01:14.061 --> 1:01:17.369
be irreverent to the piece.

1:01:17.456 --> 1:01:20.024
BASCUM:
Alright.

1:01:20.111 --> 1:01:21.547
Drop her off, first.

1:01:21.634 --> 1:01:28.119
I'll send a vehicle back
for you at nightfall.

1:01:30.599 --> 1:01:33.951
[electricity whirring]

1:01:37.171 --> 1:01:38.520
DONNIE:
I've been trying
to shoo the thoughts away,

1:01:38.607 --> 1:01:44.048
but they just keep coming.

1:01:44.135 --> 1:01:48.052
I want you out of here.

1:01:48.139 --> 1:01:54.667
But I don't know what the
fuck I'm doing anymore.

1:01:54.754 --> 1:02:01.935
Just wake up an
tell me what to do.

1:02:02.022 --> 1:02:03.545
Look...

1:02:03.632 --> 1:02:08.899
tell me what to do.

1:02:08.986 --> 1:02:12.903
Wake up.

1:02:12.990 --> 1:02:14.252
Wake up!

1:02:14.339 --> 1:02:15.993
Wake!
Up!

1:02:16.080 --> 1:02:17.646
Mom, wake up!

1:02:17.734 --> 1:02:25.916
[distant screaming]

1:02:26.003 --> 1:02:32.009
WOMAN:
Stop it, stop it,
stop it, stop it.

1:02:32.096 --> 1:02:37.797
[footsteps]

1:02:41.192 --> 1:02:43.194
MILT:
Argh!

1:02:43.281 --> 1:02:44.761
RHODA:
What have you done?

1:02:44.848 --> 1:02:46.197
MILT:
What?

1:02:46.284 --> 1:02:47.938
RHODA:
You killed
one of his men.

1:02:48.025 --> 1:02:50.462
MILT:
What, no.

1:02:50.549 --> 1:02:52.507
RHODA:
How did you
injure yourself?

1:02:52.594 --> 1:02:57.556
MILT:
I was attacked,
that animal-child of his.

1:02:57.643 --> 1:03:00.211
RHODA:
Well, one of
his men is missing.

1:03:00.298 --> 1:03:03.214
Their level of alarm
is heightening.

1:03:03.301 --> 1:03:05.564
We must move immediately.

1:03:05.651 --> 1:03:08.741
MILT:
Shouldn't we
let things simmer?

1:03:08.828 --> 1:03:10.525
Stake it back out
in a week or so.

1:03:10.612 --> 1:03:12.136
RHODA:
He's still comfortable.

1:03:12.223 --> 1:03:15.400
Unsuspecting.

1:03:15.487 --> 1:03:18.316
If something else goes wrong,

1:03:18.403 --> 1:03:20.971
opportunity may be gone forever.

1:03:21.058 --> 1:03:23.843
MILT:
Doing anything
now would be foolish.

1:03:23.930 --> 1:03:25.802
Now we need
to send you back in

1:03:25.889 --> 1:03:27.629
and wait for things
to stabilize.

1:03:27.716 --> 1:03:31.546
Hell, we haven't even
found his currency.

1:03:31.633 --> 1:03:33.548
RHODA:
It's in his wardrobe.

1:03:33.635 --> 1:03:36.247
Just as I suspected.

1:03:36.334 --> 1:03:39.903
The key is tethered
to his back brace.

1:03:39.990 --> 1:03:43.950
There's plenty for
the boy's mother.

1:03:44.037 --> 1:03:46.344
MILT:
All the more reason
to not act in haste and

1:03:46.431 --> 1:03:49.216
jeopardize losing it.

1:03:49.303 --> 1:03:51.131
Just give it a day or so.

1:03:51.218 --> 1:03:53.133
RHODA:
Stop it and listen!

1:03:53.220 --> 1:03:55.788
[indistinct]

1:03:55.875 --> 1:03:57.659
MILT:
What the hell's
wrong with you?

1:03:57.746 --> 1:03:59.792
I lose a plum-sized chunk of
my shoulder and you expect us

1:03:59.879 --> 1:04:01.446
to go prancing in to a
death-den full of men

1:04:01.533 --> 1:04:04.536
on high alert!

1:04:06.059 --> 1:04:10.194
RHODA:
I'm sorry.

1:04:10.281 --> 1:04:12.718
I'm at my end.

1:04:24.425 --> 1:04:27.254
MILT:
Alright.

1:04:27.341 --> 1:04:29.822
Then we finish it.

1:04:29.909 --> 1:04:31.650
Tonight.

1:04:31.737 --> 1:04:39.788
♪ [somber music]

1:05:08.121 --> 1:05:09.731
[door slams]

1:05:11.646 --> 1:05:19.306
[footsteps]

1:05:25.791 --> 1:05:30.622
MAN:
What depravity must a man
have inside him

1:05:30.709 --> 1:05:37.237
to do that to a female?

1:05:37.324 --> 1:05:41.894
They were just trying to
put food on their table.

1:05:45.419 --> 1:05:50.076
I know your family has felt
the sting of Bascum's evil

1:05:50.163 --> 1:05:53.514
more than any.

1:05:53.601 --> 1:06:02.828
But I want you to know
that I have felt it too.

1:06:02.915 --> 1:06:07.050
The woman I love was one
of his first victims.

1:06:10.053 --> 1:06:15.493
He may not have
cut off a limb,

1:06:15.580 --> 1:06:19.410
or turned her into
an experiment.

1:06:23.588 --> 1:06:26.330
But he made his mark.

1:06:30.899 --> 1:06:36.557
She was 12 years old.

1:06:36.644 --> 1:06:38.298
They were cousins.

1:06:42.433 --> 1:06:47.438
So when we heard he had
become a man of power,

1:06:49.483 --> 1:06:57.448
a symbol of justice, we had
no other choice but to act.

1:07:02.235 --> 1:07:08.111
In the pursuit of bloodshed,
it's always in a man's nature

1:07:08.198 --> 1:07:12.289
to question the
integrity of his actions.

1:07:15.205 --> 1:07:19.644
But when that thought
starts to roast inside you,

1:07:19.731 --> 1:07:25.563
you come back to this place.

1:07:25.650 --> 1:07:29.306
To these women.

1:07:29.393 --> 1:07:34.311
And you pluck that doubt
right out of your mind.

1:07:38.489 --> 1:07:39.794
[pats]

1:07:39.881 --> 1:07:44.799
[♪♪♪]

1:07:56.985 --> 1:08:03.122
[men groaning and gurgling]

1:08:03.209 --> 1:08:11.217
[♪♪♪]

1:09:01.049 --> 1:09:09.057
RHODA:
♪ [humming]

1:09:14.585 --> 1:09:17.109
BASCUM:
Shall I remove the brace?

1:09:17.196 --> 1:09:18.197
RHODA:
Shh.

1:09:18.283 --> 1:09:21.026
BASCUM:
Oh.

1:09:21.112 --> 1:09:24.856
RHODA:
♪ [humming]

1:09:24.943 --> 1:09:32.951
♪ [singing in other language]

1:09:41.742 --> 1:09:45.702
[♪♪♪]

1:09:45.790 --> 1:09:47.661
[squelching]

1:09:47.747 --> 1:09:55.321
[♪♪♪]

1:09:55.407 --> 1:09:58.324
[footsteps]

1:09:58.411 --> 1:10:06.419
[♪♪♪]

1:10:08.769 --> 1:10:11.728
[thud]

1:10:11.816 --> 1:10:20.433
[♪♪♪]

1:10:20.520 --> 1:10:26.612
[gurgling]

1:10:26.700 --> 1:10:34.708
[♪♪♪]

1:10:41.976 --> 1:10:48.244
[coins jangling]

1:10:48.331 --> 1:10:54.380
[♪♪♪]

1:10:54.467 --> 1:10:56.382
[squelch]

1:10:56.469 --> 1:11:04.477
[♪♪♪]

1:11:07.045 --> 1:11:11.049
BASCUM:
[moaning]

1:11:11.136 --> 1:11:19.275
RHODA:
[singing]

1:11:19.362 --> 1:11:27.370
[♪♪♪]

1:11:34.550 --> 1:11:36.422
[dart clatters]

1:11:36.509 --> 1:11:41.427
MAN:
Argh!

1:11:42.514 --> 1:11:44.300
RHODA:
Ah!

1:11:44.387 --> 1:11:50.218
[♪♪♪]

1:12:10.413 --> 1:12:12.458
[door rattles]

1:12:17.028 --> 1:12:19.073
BASCUM:
[indistinct]

1:12:19.160 --> 1:12:23.339
What can we do for you?

1:12:27.125 --> 1:12:30.693
MILT:
Let her go.

1:12:30.781 --> 1:12:34.480
BASCUM:
Rhoda?

1:12:34.567 --> 1:12:35.916
Do you know this man?

1:12:36.003 --> 1:12:37.701
RHODA:
Ah!

1:12:38.702 --> 1:12:39.833
[squelching]

1:12:39.920 --> 1:12:40.965
[rustling]

1:12:41.052 --> 1:12:45.273
BASCUM:
[groans]

1:13:06.904 --> 1:13:11.996
Well, what happens now?

1:13:12.083 --> 1:13:20.047
[coughs]

1:13:20.134 --> 1:13:28.186
♪ [morose music]

1:14:09.967 --> 1:14:12.535
DONNIE:
Come on, come on.

1:14:12.621 --> 1:14:20.630
[♪♪♪]

1:14:25.504 --> 1:14:30.596
[clattering]

1:14:30.683 --> 1:14:34.948
[♪♪♪]

1:14:35.035 --> 1:14:40.737
[rustling]

1:14:40.824 --> 1:14:48.832
[♪♪♪]

1:15:31.788 --> 1:15:35.356
DONNIE:
Where the
fuck's the money?

1:15:35.443 --> 1:15:37.054
MAN:
Bascum was a
man of principle,

1:15:37.141 --> 1:15:39.491
he wasn't concerned
with money.

1:15:39.577 --> 1:15:41.449
Here, sell this.

1:15:41.537 --> 1:15:42.712
Take it.

1:15:42.799 --> 1:15:47.673
Have it all.

1:15:47.760 --> 1:15:52.504
[distant footsteps]

1:15:52.591 --> 1:16:00.556
RHODA:
You really think
money would help your mother?

1:16:12.742 --> 1:16:15.309
[thud]

1:16:34.241 --> 1:16:39.202
WOMAN [echoing]:
Tell me it's not true what
they're saying about you.

1:16:39.290 --> 1:16:41.074
WOMAN [echoing]:
It wasn't that long ago,
almost everyone would have

1:16:41.161 --> 1:16:43.903
told you Bascum is
nothing but wicked.

1:16:43.990 --> 1:16:47.210
And now all of a
sudden he's back?

1:16:47.298 --> 1:16:53.173
MAN:
You have no idea
what harm you've caused.

1:16:53.260 --> 1:16:55.959
DONNIE:
I don't care what's
floating around out there.

1:16:56.046 --> 1:17:00.746
As long as she's okay.

1:17:00.833 --> 1:17:02.313
MAN:
I've got something with a
little more kick that can

1:17:02.400 --> 1:17:04.663
help you forget all of this.

1:17:05.882 --> 1:17:13.889
[♪♪♪]

1:17:30.602 --> 1:17:32.691
HAROLD:
Don't bother.

1:17:32.778 --> 1:17:35.520
Nobody touches the
soaps these days.

1:17:35.607 --> 1:17:38.871
BRENTON:
Oh, but it was
such a staple of the care--.

1:17:38.958 --> 1:17:40.525
[door squeaks]

1:17:40.612 --> 1:17:42.222
BRENTON:
What can
we do for you?

1:17:42.309 --> 1:17:44.964
I'm afraid if you want a
room you need to purchase a...

1:17:45.050 --> 1:17:46.400
pillow.

1:17:46.487 --> 1:17:48.402
MAN:
I knew it!

1:17:48.489 --> 1:17:50.840
You lying whore!

1:17:50.927 --> 1:17:53.146
[woman screaming]

1:17:53.233 --> 1:17:55.583
BRENTON:
You think
I should, um...

1:17:55.671 --> 1:17:56.976
Intervene?

1:17:57.063 --> 1:17:58.804
HAROLD:
What are you gonna do?

1:17:58.891 --> 1:18:00.980
MAN:
I didn't know!

1:18:02.286 --> 1:18:06.550
WOMAN: Ow!
MAN: Come on.

1:18:06.638 --> 1:18:08.118
WOMAN:
Wait, wait, I
need my coin purse.

1:18:08.205 --> 1:18:12.035
MAN:
Forget about
your coin purse!

1:18:12.121 --> 1:18:16.779
BRENTON:
I, uh, I'm
sorry, Mr Harold.

1:18:16.866 --> 1:18:21.218
I wish I could administer that
firm hand of justice, but...

1:18:21.305 --> 1:18:23.394
HAROLD:
It's not your gift.

1:18:27.224 --> 1:18:29.443
BRENTON:
Right.

1:18:30.401 --> 1:18:38.452
♪ [morose music]

1:18:40.106 --> 1:18:44.763
[woman crying]

1:18:44.850 --> 1:18:52.858
[♪♪♪]

1:19:11.311 --> 1:19:13.400
MAN:
Take a detour,
find your fix.

1:19:13.487 --> 1:19:15.446
Your desire is our command.

1:19:15.532 --> 1:19:17.621
WOMAN:
There's no
need to be bashful,

1:19:17.709 --> 1:19:19.666
have you heard of
Welded Apprentice?

1:19:19.755 --> 1:19:22.322
Only 50 cents per 15 minutes.

1:19:22.409 --> 1:19:23.933
BRENTON:
Uh, no
thank you, ma'am.

1:19:24.020 --> 1:19:29.242
[♪♪♪]

1:19:29.329 --> 1:19:35.945
[footsteps]

1:19:37.337 --> 1:19:45.344
DONNIE:
[gasping]

1:19:47.347 --> 1:19:49.915
[squealing]

1:19:50.002 --> 1:19:52.004
[thud]

1:19:52.091 --> 1:20:00.099
[footsteps]

1:20:13.939 --> 1:20:21.947
[gasping]

1:20:31.174 --> 1:20:34.264
MAN:
Hey, hey.

1:20:34.351 --> 1:20:38.702
Hey!

1:20:47.277 --> 1:20:50.976
You keep 'em cleaner next
time I'll get you more.

1:20:51.063 --> 1:20:56.199
[rustling]

1:21:02.422 --> 1:21:10.430
[♪♪♪]

1:21:15.261 --> 1:21:17.523
MAN:
When the
sea was poisoned,

1:21:17.611 --> 1:21:20.963
I remember feeling such a
burden as if I was somehow

1:21:21.050 --> 1:21:23.487
responsible.

1:21:23.574 --> 1:21:26.359
Could I have...

1:21:26.446 --> 1:21:27.534
done more?

1:21:27.621 --> 1:21:32.409
Could I have stopped it?

1:21:32.496 --> 1:21:35.934
There are so few things in
this universe that are truly

1:21:36.021 --> 1:21:43.246
edifying, things we need
to cultivate, to foster.

1:21:43.333 --> 1:21:47.511
And I really believe your
mind is one of them, Bean.

1:21:49.643 --> 1:21:51.602
I've got some unique
opportunities I want you

1:21:51.689 --> 1:21:53.603
to consider.

1:21:53.691 --> 1:21:57.085
Time when we can
hone in and...

1:21:57.173 --> 1:22:02.743
you know, figure out what
makes that crafty noggin tick.

1:22:02.830 --> 1:22:05.137
So how about we make
a weekly commitment--.

1:22:05.224 --> 1:22:06.530
BRENTON:
Okay, Bean.

1:22:06.617 --> 1:22:09.750
It's time to go.

1:22:09.837 --> 1:22:11.621
MAN:
See you Monday, Bean.

1:22:20.196 --> 1:22:23.068
BRENTON:
Your knapsack
feels pretty light.

1:22:23.155 --> 1:22:24.330
You get your books?

1:22:24.416 --> 1:22:26.289
BEAN:
I left 'em in my desk.

1:22:26.376 --> 1:22:28.073
BRENTON:
They won't do
you much good there.

1:22:28.160 --> 1:22:29.466
BEAN:
There's no
class tomorrow.

1:22:29.553 --> 1:22:30.946
BRENTON:
What?

1:22:31.032 --> 1:22:33.296
BEAN:
Girls don't go
on Fridays anymore.

1:22:33.383 --> 1:22:35.166
BRENTON:
Jeepers.

1:22:36.690 --> 1:22:40.607
[electricity buzzing]

1:22:40.693 --> 1:22:42.827
BRENTON:
I was reading
through the Atlas,

1:22:42.914 --> 1:22:46.874
saw there's a whole section
of terrain north of the basin.

1:22:46.962 --> 1:22:49.007
I was thinking maybe we could
double up on Sunday chores
and--.

1:22:49.094 --> 1:22:51.009
Would you give it up already?

1:22:51.096 --> 1:22:53.838
If Donnie wanted to
be here, he'd be here.

1:22:57.276 --> 1:23:00.323
[coughing]

1:23:00.410 --> 1:23:02.151
[fly buzzing]

1:23:07.547 --> 1:23:11.073
[bird cawing]

1:23:22.344 --> 1:23:23.781
[slow footsteps]

1:23:24.695 --> 1:23:26.914
[rustling]

1:23:34.400 --> 1:23:36.924
[screaming]

1:23:37.012 --> 1:23:41.451
WOMAN:
♪ Can't buy a billabong,
under the shade ♪

1:23:41.538 --> 1:23:44.148
♪ of a coolibah tree,

1:23:44.236 --> 1:23:47.848
♪ and he watched and he
sang and he waited 'til he--. ♪

1:23:47.934 --> 1:23:49.937
MAN:
Hey, stop, alright?

1:23:50.025 --> 1:23:52.157
Stop it right now.

1:23:52.244 --> 1:23:56.683
WOMAN:
♪ Billabong you'll come
a-waltzing Matilda with me. ♪

1:23:56.770 --> 1:23:58.294
NURSE:
Let's go!

1:23:58.380 --> 1:24:02.080
WOMAN:
♪ --waltzing Matilda--
♪ argh!

1:24:02.166 --> 1:24:03.864
Help me.
It hurts.

1:24:03.951 --> 1:24:06.215
NURSE:
I've heard that
from you before.

1:24:09.609 --> 1:24:11.523
[footsteps approach]

1:24:11.611 --> 1:24:13.787
WOMAN:
Nothing new
to report, Brenton.

1:24:13.874 --> 1:24:15.789
A few days ago I thought
I thought I saw a twitch

1:24:15.876 --> 1:24:18.791
in her knuckle, but my guess
is it was involuntary.

1:24:18.879 --> 1:24:21.534
BRENTON:
Well, it can't
be a bad thing, right?

1:24:21.621 --> 1:24:23.362
WOMAN:
I couldn't
say either way.

1:24:23.449 --> 1:24:26.235
We haven't had too much
one-on-one time lately.

1:24:26.322 --> 1:24:27.540
BRENTON:
Are we sure this
apparatus is still doing

1:24:27.627 --> 1:24:29.541
as good as it's supposed to?

1:24:29.629 --> 1:24:32.850
WOMAN:
Brenton, our medical personal is
lean as a duck breast.

1:24:32.937 --> 1:24:36.071
Now's not the time for
anyone to get experimental.

1:24:37.072 --> 1:24:41.815
[footsteps retreating]

1:24:49.954 --> 1:24:52.391
BRENTON:
Hey, come on.

1:24:52.478 --> 1:24:54.698
I know you're in
there, alright?

1:24:54.785 --> 1:24:56.830
[knocking]

1:24:56.916 --> 1:24:58.093
BRENTON:
Wake up.

1:25:01.574 --> 1:25:04.534
I could really
use you right now.

1:25:05.839 --> 1:25:09.713
[steady breathing]

1:25:09.800 --> 1:25:12.846
DONNIE:
[heavy breathing]

1:25:12.933 --> 1:25:16.589
[rodent squealing]

1:25:26.817 --> 1:25:34.868
[♪♪♪]

1:26:04.550 --> 1:26:06.552
[bird cawing]

1:26:06.639 --> 1:26:13.777
[♪♪♪]

1:26:13.864 --> 1:26:17.911
[birds cawing]

1:26:28.313 --> 1:26:32.187
[rustling]

1:26:38.496 --> 1:26:40.412
DONNIE:
Argh!

1:26:40.499 --> 1:26:41.934
[coughs]

1:26:42.022 --> 1:26:48.855
♪ [solemn music]

1:26:53.382 --> 1:26:54.513
[labored breathing]

1:26:54.600 --> 1:27:01.346
[footsteps]

1:27:01.433 --> 1:27:08.266
DONNIE:
Leave!

1:27:08.353 --> 1:27:10.746
Leave!

1:27:10.834 --> 1:27:13.793
MAN:
What?

1:27:13.880 --> 1:27:15.839
DONNIE:
Leave!

1:27:15.925 --> 1:27:17.841
MAN:
I'm here for some skins.

1:27:17.928 --> 1:27:20.322
DONNIE:
Leave!

1:27:20.409 --> 1:27:21.540
Leave!

1:27:22.454 --> 1:27:23.847
Leave!

1:27:25.282 --> 1:27:30.505
[heavy breathing]

1:27:30.593 --> 1:27:35.554
[rodent squealing]

1:27:35.641 --> 1:27:43.648
[fire crackling]

1:27:50.960 --> 1:27:59.012
[door squeaking]

1:28:22.688 --> 1:28:27.344
[♪♪♪]

1:28:27.432 --> 1:28:35.440
[squeaking]

1:28:37.616 --> 1:28:45.624
♪ [emotional music]

1:29:03.686 --> 1:29:10.083
[static buzzing]

1:29:12.999 --> 1:29:14.958
[static wavers]

1:29:15.045 --> 1:29:17.047
MAN:
-- please advance--
immediately --

1:29:17.134 --> 1:29:19.049
please report --.

1:29:19.136 --> 1:29:25.621
[static wavers]

1:29:40.287 --> 1:29:45.249
[dishes clatter]

1:29:48.773 --> 1:29:54.476
MAN:
Here for more piggy tips.

1:29:54.563 --> 1:29:57.434
SHERI:
I've been more than fair
lending out pork to y'all.

1:29:57.522 --> 1:29:58.827
[clattering]

1:29:58.915 --> 1:30:00.568
MAN:
I want more piggy tips!

1:30:00.656 --> 1:30:03.702
SHERI:
Well I can't
give away all my meat.

1:30:03.789 --> 1:30:05.617
And besides, it's chained up.

1:30:05.704 --> 1:30:07.271
Ugh.

1:30:07.358 --> 1:30:10.883
MAN:
Get as much
as you can carry!

1:30:10.969 --> 1:30:15.714
You know I cherish
your piggy tips.

1:30:15.800 --> 1:30:17.585
They're tender and tasty.

1:30:17.673 --> 1:30:21.807
They got just the right
amount of moisture.

1:30:21.894 --> 1:30:23.068
Argh!

1:30:23.156 --> 1:30:31.164
♪ [classical music]

1:30:33.950 --> 1:30:37.648
DONNIE:
Get the
fuck out of here.

1:30:37.736 --> 1:30:41.392
[clattering]

1:30:41.478 --> 1:30:43.829
DONNIE:
Take him with you!

1:30:43.916 --> 1:30:49.443
♪ [classical music]

1:30:49.531 --> 1:30:53.796
SHERI:
Damn it, Donnie, do
you have any realization

1:30:53.883 --> 1:30:56.276
[indistinct]

1:30:56.362 --> 1:30:58.496
We didn't know if
you were living.

1:30:58.583 --> 1:31:05.982
[indistinct]

1:31:06.068 --> 1:31:10.594
We prayed and we prayed.

1:31:10.682 --> 1:31:12.945
What'd your momma say?

1:31:13.032 --> 1:31:14.599
Oh, look at you.

1:31:14.686 --> 1:31:17.776
You're nothing but a
sack of flesh and bones.

1:31:17.862 --> 1:31:20.300
We need to get
some meat in you.

1:31:20.387 --> 1:31:21.911
Let's get some meat in you.

1:31:21.998 --> 1:31:24.174
DONNIE:
You mind sacking up
a couple platters?

1:31:24.261 --> 1:31:26.655
SHERI:
One for you and...

1:31:26.742 --> 1:31:29.135
DONNIE:
And one for the folks
at the centre.

1:31:29.222 --> 1:31:31.311
I should get there
before closing time.

1:31:31.398 --> 1:31:32.791
SHERI:
Say no more.

1:31:32.878 --> 1:31:38.884
[♪♪♪]

1:31:38.971 --> 1:31:44.673
[shouting outside]

1:31:44.760 --> 1:31:48.154
[♪♪♪]

1:31:48.241 --> 1:31:49.460
MAN:
I'll be gentle.

1:31:49.547 --> 1:31:56.946
[♪♪♪]

1:31:57.032 --> 1:32:01.864
SHERI:
It's awful what
happened to this place.

1:32:01.951 --> 1:32:07.217
DONNIE:
Maybe it's
time to make it better.

1:32:09.915 --> 1:32:12.091
SHERI:
Go on.

1:32:12.178 --> 1:32:13.136
I'll close up and bring
a whole sack of meat

1:32:13.223 --> 1:32:15.921
for everybody.

1:32:16.008 --> 1:32:18.228
DONNIE:
Don't close up for me.

1:32:18.315 --> 1:32:19.838
SHERI:
That's enough of that.

1:32:19.925 --> 1:32:22.885
It's time to celebrate.

1:32:22.972 --> 1:32:27.498
[explosion]

1:32:27.585 --> 1:32:29.369
SHERI:
No.

1:32:29.456 --> 1:32:31.371
DONNIE:
What the hell
are you doing, let's go.

1:32:31.458 --> 1:32:33.678
SHERI:
If it's coming I
ought to be here to face it.

1:32:33.764 --> 1:32:35.375
Shoo!

1:32:35.462 --> 1:32:37.508
Shoo, you, go on.

1:32:37.594 --> 1:32:39.118
Shoo.

1:32:39.205 --> 1:32:41.512
[footsteps]

1:32:41.599 --> 1:32:45.429
[siren sounding]

1:32:45.516 --> 1:32:47.736
SHERI:
I'm staying
with my meats.

1:32:47.823 --> 1:32:55.831
[♪♪♪]

1:33:15.590 --> 1:33:18.723
[explosion]

1:33:18.809 --> 1:33:26.818
[siren sounding]

1:33:42.007 --> 1:33:47.491
[explosion]

1:33:49.972 --> 1:33:57.980
[electricity humming]

1:34:17.347 --> 1:34:19.088
DONNIE:
I'm sorry.

1:34:25.702 --> 1:34:27.662
BEAN:
Are you gonna
go check on her?

1:34:34.190 --> 1:34:37.715
[footsteps]

1:34:42.981 --> 1:34:50.989
♪ [apocalyptic music]

1:35:08.833 --> 1:35:14.709
[♪♪♪]

1:36:30.393 --> 1:36:31.873
DONNIE:
[grunting]

1:36:34.832 --> 1:36:42.840
[♪♪♪]

1:37:09.040 --> 1:37:15.830
[♪♪♪]
